freshwater availability and water fetching distance affect child health in sub saharan africa fse freeman spogli institute for international studies woods institute for the environment center on food security and the environment stanford university fsi centers & programs research centers center on democracy development and the rule of law center for international security and cooperation center on food security and the environment stanford health policy the europe center walter h shorenstein asia pacific research center research programs program on energy and sustainable development rural education action program educational programs stanford program on international and cross cultural education inter university center for japanese language studies ford dorsey program in international policy studies affiliated programs center for innovation in global health research programs & projects by expert by topic by geographic area publications featured publications by author by topic by geographic area people events upcoming recent with papers podcasts & video news recent opinion around the web photo galleries about fse about the center annual report map & directions contact us about fsi support fsi research areas climate and agriculture aquaculture biofuels crop and livestock systems agricultural innovation deadly connections food and nutrition security reap quick links global food policy and food security symposium series teaching fse enewsletter community follow us on twitter foodsecurity_su publications send by email share online share on facebook share on twitter share on google freshwater availability and water fetching distance affect child health in sub saharan africa journal article authors amy pickering stanford woods institute for the environment jenna davis stanford university published by environmental science and technology vol 46 no 4 page s 2391 2397 2012 currently more than two thirds of the population in africa must leave their home to fetch water for drinking and domestic use the time burden of water fetching has been suggested to influence the volume of water collected by households as well as time spent on income generating activities and child care however little is known about the potential health benefits of reducing water fetching distances data from almost 200 000 demographic and health surveys carried out in 26 countries were used to assess the relationship between household walk time to water source and child health outcomes to estimate the causal effect of decreased water fetching time on health geographic variation in freshwater availability was employed as an instrumental variable for one way walk time to water source in a two stage regression model time spent walking to a household's main water source was found to be a significant determinant of under five child health a 15 min decrease in one way walk time to water source is associated with a 41 average relative reduction in diarrhea prevalence improved anthropometric indicators of child nutritional status and a 11 relative reduction in under five child mortality these results suggest that reducing the time cost of fetching water should be a priority for water infrastructure investments in africa download html+ go to site external http pubs acs org doi abs 10.1021 parent research deadly connections climate change disease poverty and conflict rural health & development at the food water nexus fsi stanford fse project topics children's health science and technology water sub saharan africa search fse search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news in sub saharan africa a shorter walk to water saves lives march 5 2012 fse fsi stanford news publications of interest smallholder irrigation as a poverty alleviation tool in sub saharan africa jennifer burney rosamond l naylor world development vol 40 2011 html+ cover warming increases risk of civil war in africa marshall burke edward miguel shanker satyanath john dykema david lobell proceedings of the national academy of sciences 2009 html+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4920 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
